.TH GIT-PR 1 "2026-07-07" "git-tools" "Git Tools Manual"
.SH NAME
git-pr \- check out the branch for a GitHub pull request by number
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B git pr
.I NUMBER
.br
.B git pr
[\fB\-h\fR|\fB\-\-help\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
Check out the head branch of GitHub pull request #\fINUMBER\fR, always up to
date. It runs
.BR "gh pr checkout" ,
which creates the branch or fast-forwards an existing local branch to the PR's
latest \(em so you are never left on a stale copy. For merged or closed PRs
whose branch has been deleted from
.IR origin ,
it falls back to
.IR refs/pull/<NUMBER>/head ,
which GitHub keeps around, into a local branch of the same name.
.PP
Branches are stamped with their PR number
.RB ( "branch.<name>.gtools-pr" ),
so if the GitHub CLI cannot reach GitHub,
.B git pr
falls back to switching to the stamped local branch as-is (without updating it),
letting it still work offline.
.PP
Named
.I git pr
rather than
.IR git switch :
git always prefers its built-in
.B switch
over a script, so a custom
.I git-switch
could never run.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Show usage and exit.
.SH REQUIREMENTS
Requires the GitHub CLI
.RB ( gh ),
authenticated for the repository
.RB ( "gh auth login" ). Only the offline fallback (switching to an
already-stamped branch) works without it.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
.B git pr 923
Check out the head branch of PR #923.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR git-done (1),
.BR git-sync (1),
.BR git-sweep (1),
.BR gh (1)
